WEBVTT

00:05.313 --> 00:10.578
So you'd had enough of the military and you didn't 
want to go back into a military setting. Yeah,

00:11.139 --> 00:19.087
you've got to go into it wholeheartedly again or 
stay out of it. So I decided that Texas A&M wasn't

00:20.488 --> 00:24.993
for me. My mission at that time was to get a college 
degree to satisfy my family. and then go do what I

00:32.903 --> 00:35.567
damn well pleased. Well, why did you go on 
eventually then to get a PhD? During that process,

00:39.472 --> 00:42.537
did you get interested in education? No,

00:43.458 --> 00:48.265
I taught a year. I made exceptionally good grades 
in Baylor because I always had to make good grades

00:49.487 --> 00:59.641
to carry that extra load. And so I reached the point 
along about 19, 22, where I could finish in one

01:04.561 --> 01:14.170
summer school at Baylor. While I was in summer 
school finishing the,

01:16.372 --> 01:34.568
to get the diploma ahead of the game, a

01:16.372 --> 01:34.568
teacher, a superintendent from little town up 
close to Corsicana. Came down and was begging a

01:38.815 --> 01:58.072
fellow that had taught school under him 
previously to come back up there and be principal

01:38.815 --> 01:58.072
of his high school for another year or two at Lemon 
Grove. This guy says, I can't accept the job. He

02:01.796 --> 02:03.357
says, I'm offered a college job up at Benton in the 
math department as an instructor. If I can get my

02:11.459 --> 02:20.731
foot on the ladder with a college, I should do that 
rather than messing around with high schools

02:11.459 --> 02:20.731
anymore. And he says, so he said, well, have you a 
friend down here that could do the job? He says,

02:30.803 --> 02:33.647
yeah, there he is, walking across the campus. 
Well, that happened to be me. And he says, you can do

02:36.706 --> 02:42.174
any damn thing he wants to. And if you can persuade 
him to take this job, he says, I'll call him over

02:42.194 --> 02:47.802
here. Well, on that recommendation, he offered me 
a job up there. Of course, we had quite a

02:53.390 --> 02:55.693
conversation about it. He paid a good salary for 
nine months. I had just turned down a job on a

03:01.522 --> 03:14.582
newspaper that offered me $25 a week for the first 
six weeks. And if at the end of the six weeks I was

03:15.984 --> 03:23.415
still making good, they'd raise my salary to $30 a 
week. And by God, from there on I was on my own. That

03:30.530 --> 03:32.673
was the journalistic world. Well, in competition 
with $160 a month for nine months, only nine

03:34.195 --> 03:56.685
months, at Blooming Grove under this very fine 
fellow

03:34.195 --> 03:56.685
that was really hard up for, what he was trying to do 
was to get another man or two on the faculty besides

03:34.195 --> 03:56.685
himself. See, man. I went up there and I finished 
that job and

04:00.702 --> 04:26.665
went back down to Baylor and the old dean that, I 
can't think of his name at the moment,

04:00.702 --> 04:26.665
says, how did you get along teaching school up 
there? I said, well, I enjoyed teaching school. I

04:31.583 --> 04:34.988
says, they had me doing every damn thing under the 
sun.

04:38.333 --> 04:53.114
If they organized, they didn't have enough boys to 
really organize a football team, but they did

04:38.333 --> 04:53.114
scrape together about 15 that

04:38.333 --> 04:53.114
got suits up for them, and I says, I wound up 
coaching the team. I says, I didn't know how to

04:54.275 --> 04:58.221
throw a football. I says, everything that 
happened. And furthermore, the churches had

05:05.712 --> 05:21.611
apparently decided that they had, each one of 
them, the Baptist church was entitled to half the

05:05.712 --> 05:21.611
faculty, and the Methodist church was entitled to 
the other half. Well, I didn't fit into either

05:22.532 --> 05:25.576
half. So I wasn't gonna take on any, Each one of 
them, yeah, sure, we need somebody to teach this,

05:31.051 --> 05:36.196
teach that. Everything, every extracurricular 
piece of work that came up, I had to do it. I told him,

05:43.243 --> 05:51.711
I says, I enjoy teaching, but I says, I was 
reelected. But he said, if I can get a college job

05:51.731 --> 05:58.358
where I, responsible only for teaching and 
papers. I says, I think that'd be pretty good, but

06:03.868 --> 06:20.250
if you haven't got anything like that, or if the 
placement bureau here can't offer me something

06:03.868 --> 06:20.250
better than that, then I'm quitting the teaching 
profession. And

06:20.671 --> 06:26.899
he said, well, you shouldn't do that. He gave me 
quite a song and dance. flattered me about my

06:29.793 --> 06:38.845
record for A's and honor points and all that stuff. 
And said, you, the teaching, you ought to stay in

06:38.865 --> 06:48.579
it. And so I said, well, you can tell that to the 
placement bureau here. Something comes along.

06:59.780 --> 07:00.801
let me know.

07:05.227 --> 07:15.820
This was actually at the, I'd already told them 
that I wasn't coming back to Blooming Grove, but I

07:05.227 --> 07:15.820
was still, I went back to work up there. And before I 
finished the job,

07:17.021 --> 07:27.694
I got an offer from

07:17.021 --> 07:27.694
Gulf Coast Military Academy. and to teach

07:29.497 --> 07:43.817
just about whatever I could teach that they might 
want you to teach.

07:44.618 --> 07:59.419
So, I took a shot at that and got down there and in a 
way it was worse than blooming a grove because

08:00.395 --> 08:12.513
There, I

08:00.395 --> 08:12.513
became what they called a tactical officer in 
addition to my other duties. My other duties were a

08:13.775 --> 08:18.301
full-time teaching schedule in the forenoon. I 
was off the rest of the afternoon until drill time,

08:19.924 --> 08:29.878
and at drill time, I was out there on the drill 
field, keeping an eye on my particular company,

08:30.297 --> 08:38.368
which was the cadets in Company B. So here I was back 
in the military school without knowing it. They

08:44.496 --> 08:45.878
did pay well. They treated me handsomely. There 
was also night duty. I was billeted at one end of the

08:56.271 --> 08:59.916
dormitory that contained a battery of Company B. 
And the commandant of cadets there says, how is it

09:05.524 --> 09:12.390
that you're not in uniform? I said, hell, I'm not 
supposed to wear a uniform here. I'm a civilian. He

09:17.355 --> 09:18.777
says, to hell you are. I says, you're a tactical 
officer. I says, I wasn't hired as a tactical

09:22.521 --> 09:26.485
officer. Well, anyway, you're here and you're 
functioning. He says, I heard you dress down the

09:30.254 --> 09:40.367
company before going on parade, and you was in 
civilian clothes. He says, we can't have that. I

09:42.710 --> 09:44.152
says, what are you going to do about it? He says, 
well, we're going to commission you a second

09:45.333 --> 09:49.538
lieutenant of the reserve. Oh, I was going to ask 
you that, how you got in the reserves, and this is

09:49.558 --> 09:53.563
how. I'm going to give you a, Get your commission, 
second lieutenant of the reserve corps. I says,

10:03.027 --> 10:12.440
well,

10:03.027 --> 10:12.440
I said, I'm not taking any examination or 
anything. He says, you don't have to have any. I'll

10:15.685 --> 10:21.273
have my master sergeant

10:15.685 --> 10:21.273
picks up the papers. He'll bring them over. You 
sign your name. He says, pretty soon you'll be a

10:25.119 --> 10:28.223
second lieutenant of the reserve corps. I said, 
well, there's a hell of a lot of drill that I have

10:29.485 --> 10:40.456
forgotten and the drills in the Navy, even in 
parades, is different from the Army. I said, if I'm

10:41.357 --> 10:47.623
going to be able to service, I'd rather have the 
Navy end of it. Well, no, we don't have any Navy

10:47.683 --> 10:54.990
courses or naval officers here. I said, well, We 
had a discussion over it, but I wound up accepting

10:59.540 --> 11:06.668
the commission and put on the uniform with the rest 
of them. Now, did you have to go to meetings? Go to

11:10.031 --> 11:10.832
meetings? Go to meetings of other second 
lieutenants? No. Did they send you to any kind of a

11:16.338 --> 11:19.521
reserve training program? Hell no. And was that 
easy to get into the reserves in the 1920s? Well, if

11:24.767 --> 11:29.412
you've got the endorsement of a... professor of 
military science and tactics. I told him, I says, I

11:33.728 --> 11:51.035
don't know a damn thing about, I says, I know the 
commands for breaking from just what I know from

11:33.728 --> 11:51.035
the learned here or have or am learning. I had 
learned from reading the manual of arms infantry

11:57.016 --> 12:09.428
drill regulations, I knew how to give the commands 
to go from a column of squads to a skirmish line. The

12:11.089 --> 12:16.034
command is skirmishers blah blah blah blah. And I 
knew, all I knew was what I had learned there as a

12:16.054 --> 12:23.361
tactical officer. During the 1920s and the 1930s, 
when America was at peace, you remained the whole

12:23.932 --> 12:33.467
time in the Army Reserve. Is that not right? Well, 
let's see. You were still a reserve commissioned

12:36.732 --> 12:39.156
officer.

